The '''redback spider''' (''Latrodectus hasseltii'') is a [[species]] of venomous spider [[Endemism|endemic]] to Australia. It is a member of the worldwide genus ''[[Latrodectus]]'', the widow spiders. The female is easily recognisable by her black body with a prominent red stripe on the upper side of her abdomen. Females have a body length of about {{convert|1|cm|sigfig=1}}, while the male is smaller, being only 3<U+2013>4&nbsp;mm (0.12<U+2013>0.16&nbsp;in) long.

The female spider lives in an untidy web in warm sheltered locations, and preys on insects, spiders and lizards that it entraps, but it can live for over 100 days without food. It is preyed upon by other species of spider and [[parasitoid]] wasps. The redback is one of few arachnids which usually display [[sexual cannibalism]] while mating. The sperm is then stored in [[spermathecae]], [[organ (biology)|organs]] of the female reproductive tract, and can be used to lay several round white egg sacs.

The redback is one of the most dangerous species of spider. It has a widespread distribution in Australia, and colonies have also been established in a number of other countries. It is especially found co-located with humans and is responsible for the large majority of Australian spider bites with serious medical consequences. Its venom is [[neurotoxic]] to humans, with a small fraction of [[Spider bite#Spider venom|bites]] causing [[latrodectism]] which includes severe pain, often lasting over 24 hours. An [[antivenom]] is commercially available, and since its introduction in 1956, no deaths directly due to redback bites have been formally recorded.

==Taxonomy and naming==
Swedish arachnologist [[Tamerlan Thorell]] described the redback spider in 1870,<ref name=thorell>{{cite journal | author= Thorell, Tamerlan |year=1870|title= Araneae nonnullae Novae Hollandiae, descriptae |language=Latin |journal= <U+00D6>fversigt af Kongelige Vetenskaps-Akademiens F<U+00F6>rhandlingar, Stockholm |volume= 27 |pages= 367<U+2013>389 [369<U+2013>371] |url=http://archive.org/stream/fversigtafkongl21vetegoog}}</ref> from specimens collected in [[Rockhampton]] and [[Bowen, Queensland|Bowen]] in central Queensland.<ref name="FOPC">{{cite journal|last=Pickard-Cambridge|first=Frederick Octavius |year=1902|title=On the Spiders of the Genus ''Latrodectus'' Walckenaer|journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London|volume=1|pages=247-61 [255, 258-59]|url=http://archive.org/stream/cbarchive_101275_onthespidersofthegenuslatrodec1833/onthespidersofthegenuslatrodec1833#page/n17/mode/2up}}</ref> He named it in honour of A.W.M. van Hasselt, a colleague of his.<ref name="Species bank">{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/species-bank/sbank-treatment.pl?id=69198|title=''Latrodectus hasseltii'' (Family Theridiidae)|last=Gray|first=M. R.|date=7 February 2007|work=Department of Sustainability, Environment, Water, Population and Communities: Species Bank|publisher=Australian Government|accessdate=8 September 2013|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref> In the same paper, he named a female with an all-black abdomen ''L. scelio'',<ref name=thorell/> collected from Cape York.<ref name="FOPC"/>

German arachnologist [[Friedrich Dahl]] revised the genus in 1902 and named ''L. ancorifer'' from New Guinea,<ref name=dahl>{{cite journal | author= Dahl, Friedrich |year=1902 |language=German | title= <U+00DC>ber algebrochene Copulationsorgane m<U+00E4>nnlicher Spinnen im K<U+00F6>rper der Weibchen |journal= Sitzungsberichte der Gesellschaft Naturforschender Freunde zu Berlin |pages=36<U+2013>45 [43] |url=http://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/7931174}}</ref> which has since been regarded as conspecific.<ref name="AFD">{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/abrs/online-resources/fauna/afd/taxa/Latrodectus_hasseltii |title=Species ''Latrodectus hasseltii'' Thorell, 1870|author=Department of Sustainability, Environment, Water, Population and Communities |date=25 October  2012|work=Australian Faunal Directory |publisher=Australian Government|accessdate=8 September 2013|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref> [[Frederick Octavius Pickard-Cambridge]] questioned Dahl's separating [[species]] on what he considered minor anatomical details but the latter dismissed the former as an "ignoramus".<ref name="levi 1959"/> Pickard-Cambridge was unsure whether ''L. hasseltii'' warranted species status, though confirmed ''scelio'' and ''hasseltii'' as a single species,<ref name="FOPC"/> other researchers such as [[Ludwig Carl Christian Koch]]  noting the differences to be inconsistent.<ref name=SMH1907>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article14853380 |title=The Red-striped Spider |newspaper=[[Sydney morning herald]] |location=Sydney, New South Wales |date=23 March 1907 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia|author=Rainbow, William Joseph}}</ref> The redback was also considered by some to be conspecific with the [[katipo]] (''L. katipo''), which is native to [[New Zealand]],<ref name=Camperdown1893>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article19363887 |title=The Deadly Red-Backed Spider. |newspaper=[[The Camperdown Chronicle|Camperdown Chronicle (Vic. : 1877 <U+2013> 1954)]] |location=Vic. |date=1 June 1893  |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> though Koch regarded them as distinct.<ref name=SMH1907>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article14853380 |title=The Red-striped Spider |newspaper=[[Sydney morning herald]] |location=Sydney, New South Wales |date=23 March 1907|page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia|author=Rainbow, William Joseph}}</ref>

Arachnologist [[Herbert Walter Levi]] revised the genus ''Lactrodectus'' in 1959, studying the female sexual organs and noting their similarity across described species. He concluded the colour variations were variable across the world and were not sufficient to warrant species status, and reclassified the redback and several other species as subspecies of the black widow spider.<ref name="levi 1959">{{cite journal|last=Levi, Herbert Walter |year=1959|title=The Spider Genus ''Latrodectus'' (Araneae, Theridiidae)|journal=Transactions of the American Microscopical Society|volume=78|issue=1|pages=7<U+2013>43|jstor=3223799}}</ref>

===Current placement===
A member of the genus ''[[Latrodectus]]'' in the family [[Theridiidae]], the redback belongs in a [[clade]] with the best-known member of the group, the black widow spider (''[[Latrodectus mactans]]''), found in North America and other regions.<ref name="garb 2004"/> The katipo is the redback's closest relative.<ref name="vink"/> A 2004 molecular study supports the redback's status as distinct species, as does the unique abdomen-presenting behaviour of the male during mating.<ref name="garb 2004"/>

The close relationship between the katipo and redback is shown when mating, The male redback is able to successfully mate with a female katipo producing [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] [[offspring]]. However, the male katipo can not mate with the female redback as the male katipo is heavier than the male redback and when it approaches the web it triggers a [[predatory]] response in the female leading to the katipo being eaten before mating occurs.<ref name="Riordan">{{cite web | title =Species Profile: Katipo spider | first= Hilary Ann |last=Riordan |publisher = CanterburyNature| month = July | year = 2005 | url =http://www.canterburynature.org/species/lincoln_essays/katipo.php | accessdate = May 27, 2008}}</ref> There is evidence of interbreeding between katipo and redbacks in the wild.<ref name="vink">{{cite journal |last1=Vink|first1=Cor J.|last2=Sirvid|first2=Phil J.|last3=Malumbres-Olarte|first3=Jagoba|last4=Griffiths|first4=James W.|last5=Paquin|first5=Pierre|last6=Paterson|first6=Adrian M. |title=Species status and conservation issues of New Zealand's endemic ''Latrodectus'' spider species (Araneae: Theridiidae) |journal=[[Invertebrate Systematics]] |volume=22 |issue=6 |pages=589<U+2013>604 |year=2008 |doi=10.1071/IS08027 |issn=1445-5226 |oclc=50150601 |publisher=[[CSIRO]] Publishing |location=[[Collingwood, Victoria|Collingwood, Vic.]], Australia}}</ref>

===Common names===
The common name "redback" is derived from its distinctive red stripe along the dorsal aspect of its abdomen. Other common names include red-striped spider,<ref name=SMH1907/> red backed spider,<ref name=Queenslander1923/> red spot spider, jockey spider,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41605415 |title=Poisonous Spiders. |newspaper=[[Perth Gazette|The West Australian (Perth, WA : 1879 - 1954)]] |location=Perth, WA |date=8 January 1938  |page=19 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Murra-ngura spider, Kapara spider and the Kanna-jeri spider.<ref>{{cite book| editor = Platnick, N.; Merrett, P.; Brignoli, P. M.| year=1990| title=Advances in spider taxonomy, 1981<U+2013>1987. A supplement to Brignoli's "a catalogue of the Araneae described between 1940<U+2013>1981 | publisher=Manchester University Press | isbn=0-7190-2782-9 }}</ref>

==Description==
[[File:RedbackPottingMix.JPG|thumb|left|A juvenile female, showing typical white banding]]
[[File:Red back underside.jpg|thumb|right|The ventral side of an adult female, showing the red hourglass]]
The adult female redback has a round body about {{convert|1|cm|sigfig=1}} long, with long, slender legs. The body is a deep black colour (occasionally brownish), with a red (sometimes orange) longitudinal stripe on the upper [[abdomen]]. On the underside of the abdomen is an hourglass-shaped red/orange streak.<ref name="Amo-Redback"/> Redback spiderlings are grey with dark spots, and become darker with each [[Moulting|moult]].<ref name=SMH1907/> The female red stripe also develops through this process, starting as a red spot, then multiple spots which later merge.<ref name=SMH1907/> Juvenile females have additional white markings on the abdomen.<ref name="Amo-Redback"/>
 
The male redback is 3<U+2013>4&nbsp;mm (0.12<U+2013>0.16&nbsp;in) long and is light brown in colour, with white markings on the upper side of the abdomen and a pale hourglass marking on the underside.<ref name="Amo-Redback">{{cite web | author=Australian Museum | title=Redback Spider Fact Sheet | url=http://www.australianmuseum.net.au/Redback-Spider/ | accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref>

Another species in Australia with a similar physique, ''[[Steatoda capensis]]'', has been termed the "false redback spider", but it is uniformly black (or plum), and does not display the red stripe.<ref name=Warden1989>{{cite news |first=Ian |last=Warden |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article118118613 |title=Red-back spider that is not. |newspaper=[[Canberra Times|The Canberra Times (ACT : 1926 <U+2013> 1995)]] |location=ACT |date=12 February 1987  |page=1 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

==Ecology and behaviour==
[[File:Female redback spider.jpg|thumb|right|A redback spider sitting in its web]]

===Web===
The redback stays concealed during the day, and the female spins a web during the night,<ref name=SMH1907/> usually in the same location for most of its adult life.<ref name=Andrade2002/> The web is a disorganised, irregular tangle of fine but strong silk. The rear portion of the web forms a funnel-like retreat area where the spider and egg sacs are found. This area has vertical, sticky catching threads that run to ground attachments.<ref name="Amo-Redback"/> The vertical strands serve two purposes, it snares prey and small insects and can be lifted in the air, and secondly acts as a trip wire to alert the spider to the presence of prey or threats.<ref name=AWV_youtube>{{cite web|title=Web Design... Redback Style|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvjhc6BXQDM|publisher=Absolutely Wild Visuals|accessdate=4 September 2013|date=4 July 2011}}</ref> The horizontal strands, known as guy lines, break when prey thresh around.<ref name=AWV_youtube/> These webs are usually placed between two flat surfaces, one beneath the other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bQABY9H1h1Y |title=Red Back Spider&nbsp;<U+2014> Attenborough: Life in the Undergrowth&nbsp;<U+2014> BBC |publisher=BBC Earth |author=Attenborough, David |date=2009-08-28 |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> Rare observations suggest that they occasionally utilize dead leaves to construct a more enclosed nest.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article70575237 |title=Nature Student |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald|The Central Queensland Herald (Rockhampton, Qld. : 1930 <U+2013> 1956)]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=31 December 1936 |page=11 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Chew|first=Tony, Sandy and Peter|title=Red Back Spider - Latrodectus hasselti|url=http://www.brisbaneinsects.com/brisbane_weavers/Red_Back.htm|work=Brisbane Insects|accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Redback vers Lizard.jpg|thumb|left|A redback spider with a lizard it has captured]]

===Prey===
Redbacks usually prey on insects, but can capture larger animals that become entangled in the web, including [[king crickets]], [[trapdoor spider]]s, and small [[lizard]]s.<ref name="AustMus"/> The slater (''[[Porcellio scaber]]'') is a particularly common food item,{{sfn|McKeown|1963|p=193}} while one web was recorded with a dead mouse within.{{sfn|McKeown|1963|p=144}} Food scraps and lighting attract insect prey to areas of human activity, which brings their hunters.{{sfn|Brunet|1997|p=148}} Commonly, prey-stealing occurs where larger females take food items stored in other spiders' webs.<ref name="Amo-Redback"/> When they encounter other spiders of the same species, often including those of the opposite sex, they engage in battle, and the defeated spider is eaten.<ref name=SMH1907/> If the male is accepted by a female, it is permitted to feed on the victims snared in the female's web.<ref name=SMH1907/>

===Predators and parasitoids===
The daddy-long-legs spider (''[[Pholcus phalangioides]]'') and the giant daddy-long-legs spider (''[[Artema atlanta]]'') are known to prey on the redback spider.<ref>{{cite web|title=Redback Spider|url=http://www.qm.qld.gov.au/Find+out+about/Animals+of+Queensland/Spiders/Modern+Spiders+Infraorder+Araneomorphae/Redback+and+Brown+Widow+spiders/Redback+Spider|publisher=[[Queensland Museum]]|accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref>   ''[[Agenioideus nigricornis]]'', a [[spider wasp]], is a [[parasitoid]] of the adult redback.<ref name=Krogmann/>  Other [[Hymenoptera|wasps]] of the families [[Eurytomidae]] and [[Ichneumonidae]] have been recorded parisitising redback eggs, and mantid lacewings ([[Neuroptera]] and [[Mantispidae]]) preying on redback eggs.<ref name=Krogmann>{{cite journal |last1=Krogmann |first1=Lars |last2=Austin |first2=Andrew D.|year=2011 |title=Systematics of Australian ''Agenioideus'' Ashmead (Hymenoptera: Pompilidae) with the first record of a spider wasp parasitizing ''Latrodectus hasselti'' Thorell (redback spider). |journal=Australian Journal of Entomology |volume=51 |issue=3 |pages=166<U+2013>174 |doi=10.1111/j.1440-6055.2011.00850.x}}</ref>

==Life cycle==
[[File:Baby Latrodectus hasselti cropped.jpg|thumb|right|Redback spiderlings]]
Male spiders mature through five instars in about 45<U+2013>90 days.<ref name=Andrade2002/><ref name=AustMus/> Females mature through seven<U+2013>eight instars in about 75<U+2013>120 days.<ref name=Andrade2002/><ref name=AustMus/> Males live for up to six or seven months, while female may live between two and three years.<ref name=AustMus>{{cite web|url=http://australianmuseum.net.au/Redback-Spider |title=Redback Spider, ''Latrodectus hasselti'' |publisher=Australian Museum |date=21 June 2013 |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> Even without food, spiders may survive for an average of 100 days, and sometimes over 300 days.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Forster|first=L. M.|coauthors=Kavale, J.|title=Effects of food deprivation on Latrodectus hasselti Thorell (Araneae: Theridiidae), the Australian redback spider|journal=New Zealand Journal of Zoology|date=1 July 1989|volume=16|issue=3|pages=401<U+2013>408|doi=10.1080/03014223.1989.10422906}}</ref> Redbacks can survive temperatures from below freezing point to 40&nbsp;<U+00B0>C.<ref name="distributions paper"/>

Young redback spiders leave the maternal web by being carried on the wind. The spider extends its abdomen high in the air and produces a droplet of silk. The liquid silk is drawn out into a long [[Spider silk|gossamer]] thread that, when long enough, carries the spider away. Eventually, the silken thread will adhere to an object where the young spider will establish its own web.<ref name=AustMus/>

===Reproduction===
[[File:Latrodectus hasselti male and female.png|thumb|upright=2.0|right|Female redback guarding egg sac, note the male at left (''circled'')]]
Before a juvenile male leaves its mother's web, it builds a small sperm web on which it deposits its sperm from its gonads and then collects it back into its palp (copulatory organ), because the gonads and palp are not internally connected.<ref name=Andrade2002/> Unmated sexually-mature female redback spiders secrete [[pheremone]]s including a [[serine]] derivative (N-3-methylbutyryl-O-(S)-2-methylbutyryl-L-serine '''3''') onto their web.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Jerhot|first=Elena|coauthors=Stoltz, Jeffrey<U+2005>A.; Andrade, Maydianne<U+2005>C.<U+2005>B.; Schulz, Stefan|title=Acylated Serine Derivatives: A Unique Class of Arthropod Pheromones of the Australian Redback Spider, Latrodectus hasselti|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|date=8 March 2010|volume=49|issue=11|pages=2037<U+2013>2040|doi=10.1002/anie.200906312}}</ref> This is thought to be the sole method by which males assess a female's reproductive status, and their courtship dismantles much of the pheremone-marked web.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Stoltz|first=Jeffrey A.|coauthors=McNeil, Jeremy N.; Andrade, Maydianne C. B.|title=Males assess chemical signals to discriminate just-mated females from virgins in redback spiders|journal=Animal Behaviour|date=1 December 2007|volume=74|issue=6|pages=1669<U+2013>1674|doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2007.03.011}}</ref>

The redback spider is one of only two animals to date where the male has been found to actively assist the female in [[sexual cannibalism]]. In the process of mating, the much smaller male somersaults to place his abdomen over the female's mouthparts. In about two of three cases, the female fully consumes the male while mating continues. Males which are not eaten die of their injuries soon after mating.<ref>{{cite doi|10.1071/ZO9920001}}</ref>  Sacrifice during mating is thought to confer two advantages to the males. The first is the eating process allows for a longer period of copulation and thus fertilisation of more eggs. The second is females which have eaten a male are more likely to reject subsequent males.<ref>{{cite journal | first = Maydianne C. B. | last = Andrade | date = 5 January 1996, | title = Sexual Selection for Male Sacrifice in the Australian Redback Spider | journal = Science | volume = 271 | issue = 5245 | pages = 70<U+2013>72 | doi = 10.1126/science.271.5245.70 | url = http://www.utsc.utoronto.ca/~mandrade/pdf/Andrade96.pdf | format=PDF  | bibcode=1996Sci...271...70A}}</ref> Although this prohibits the possibility of future mating for the males, this is not a serious disadvantage, because the spiders are sufficiently sparse that only 20% of males ever find a potential mate during their lifetimes,<ref>{{cite doi|10.1093/beheco/arg015}}</ref> and in any case, the male is functionally sterile if he has used the contents of both of his paired palps in the first mating.<ref name=Andrade2002>{{cite journal|last=Andrade|first=Maydianne C. B.|coauthors=Banta, Erin M.|title=Value of male remating and functional sterility in redback spiders|journal=Animal Behaviour|year=2002|month=May|volume=63|issue=5|pages=857<U+2013>870|doi=10.1006/anbe.2002.2003}}</ref>

Some redback males have been observed using an alternative tactic that also ensures more of their genetic material is passed on. Juvenile female redbacks nearing their final moulting and adulthood have fully formed reproductive organs, but lack openings in the exoskeleton that allow access to the organs. Males will bite through the exoskeleton and deliver sperm to the organs without performing the somersault seen in males mating with adult females. The females then moult within a few days and deliver a normal clutch of eggs.<ref>{{cite conference | author=Biaggio, M. D.; Andrade, M. C. B. | title=Breaking an entry: Male Redback spiders inseminate juvenile females by ripping through their exoskeleton | booktitle=Animal Behaviour Society meeting | date=12<U+2013>16 August 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Milius|first=Susan|title=Underage spiders: males show unexpected interest in young mates|journal=Science News|date=26 August 2006|volume=190|issue=9|page=133|url=http://www.sciencenews.org/view/generic/id/7690/description/Underage_Spiders_Males_show_unexpected_interest_in_young_mates}}</ref>

Once the female has mated, the sperm is stored in one or both of her two [[spermathecae]] (sperm storage organs).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Snow|first=L. S. E.|coauthors=Andrade, M. C. B.|title=Multiple sperm storage organs facilitate female control of paternity|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|date=7 June 2005|volume=272|issue=1568|pages=1139<U+2013>1144|doi=10.1098/rspb.2005.3088}}</ref> The sperm can be used to lay several batches of eggs, over a period of up to two years (estimated from observations of closely related species),<ref name=Andrade2002/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Kaston|first=B. J.|title=Comparative Biology of American Black Widow Spiders|journal=Transactions of the San Diego Society of Natural History|year=1970|volume=16|issue=3|pages=33<U+2013>82|url=http://archive.org/stream/cbarchive_125679_comparativebiologyofamericanbl1905/comparativebiologyofamericanbl1905}}</ref>  but typically restarts pheremone production advertising her sexual availability about three months after mating.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Perampaladas|first=Kuhan|coauthors=Stoltz, J. A.; Andrade, M. C. B.|title=Mated Redback Spider Females Re-Advertise Receptivity Months after Mating|journal=Ethology|date=1 June 2008|volume=114|issue=6|pages=589<U+2013>598|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2008.01513.x}}</ref> A female spider may lay four to ten egg sacs,<ref name="Species bank"/> each of which averages around 250 eggs,<ref name=AustMus/> though can be as few as 40 or as many as 500.<ref name="Species bank"/> She prepares a shallow concave disc around 3&nbsp;mm (1/8 in) in diameter before laying eggs into it over a period of around five minutes before laying more silk to complete the sac, which becomes spherical<U+2014>the whole process taking around one and a quarter hours.{{sfn|McKeown|1963|pp=190<U+2013>191}} She can produce a new egg sac as early as one to three weeks after laying a previous one.<ref name=AustMus/> The spiderlings hatch after about 8 days and emerge from the egg sac as early as 11 days after being laid, but cooler temperatures can significantly slow the development, so that emergence does not occur for months.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Downes|first=M. F.|title=Postembryonic development of Lactrodectus hasselti Thorell (Araneae, Theridiidae)|journal=Journal of Arachnology|year=1987|volume=14|issue=3|pages=293<U+2013>301|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3705670}}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:Redback spider records map.png|thumb|upright=1.1|A distribution map of the records of redback spider specimens reported to the [[Atlas of Living Australia]]]]
The redback spider's origins are uncertain, and it may have been spread by human activities. The species was known by 1850 in South Australia, only 14 years after European settlement there, but was not reported in early spider collections in other colonies.<ref name="distributions paper"/> Because it was first found at seaports, it has even been suggested that the redback may not be native to Australia.<ref name="garb 2004">{{cite journal|last=Garb|first=Jessica E.|coauthors=Gonz<U+00E1>lez, Alda; Gillespie, Rosemary G.|title=The black widow spider genus Latrodectus (Araneae: Theridiidae): phylogeny, biogeography, and invasion history|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|year=2004|month=June|volume=31|issue=3|pages=1127<U+2013>1142|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2003.10.012|url=http://nature.berkeley.edu/~gillespie/Publications_files/GarbGonzGillMPE.pdf}}</ref> Outside urban areas, the redback is more often found in dryer habitats ranging from [[sclerophyll]] forest to desert, even as harsh as the [[Simpson Desert]].{{sfn|Brunet|1997|p=148}} It became much more common in urban areas in the early decades of the 20th century,{{sfn|McKeown|1963|p=188}} and is now found in all but the most inhospitable environments in Australia and its cities.{{sfn|Brunet|1997|p=148}} The redback spider is commonly found in close proximity to human residences. Webs are usually built in dry, dark, sheltered sites, such as among rocks, in logs, tree hollows, shrubs, old tyres, sheds, outhouses, empty tins and boxes, children's toys or under rubbish or litter.<ref name=SMH1907/><ref name="Amo-Redback"/><ref name="autogenerated3">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39366487 |title=Beware the Red-Back spider. |newspaper=[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail (Perth, WA : 1885 <U+2013> 1954)]] |location=Perth, WA |date=18 March 1954  |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Letterboxes and the undersurface of toilet seats are common sites.{{sfn|Brunet|1997|p=148}} Populations can be controlled by clearing these habitats,<ref name=CentralianAdvocate/> squashing the spiders and their eggsacs,<ref name=Warden1989/> and the use of insecticide in outhouses.<ref name=CentralianAdvocate>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59838671 |title=Redback Plague Continues. |newspaper=[[Centralian Advocate|Centralian Advocate (Alice Springs, NT : 1947 <U+2013> 1954)]] |location=Alice Springs, NT |date=26 January 1951 |page=13 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Some experts recommend against the use of spider insecticides, because of their toxicity, and the fact that redbacks are rapid recolonists anyway.<ref name=Warden1989/>

===Introductions===
There is an established population of redback spiders in [[Osaka]], Japan.<ref name="distributions paper"/><ref>{{cite doi|10.1603/0022-2585-41.3.269}}</ref> They are thought to have arrived in Japan on the outside of airliners, or carried in cargoes of wood chips.<ref name="Vic">{{cite web | author= Victoria Museum | title= Redback Spider | url= http://www.museum.vic.gov.au/spidersparlour/spider13.htm | accessdate=18 February 2007}}</ref>
In 2008, redback spiders were found in Fukuoka, Japan. Over 700 have been found near the container terminal in Hakata Bay, Fukuoka City.<ref name="xinhuanet1">{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/health/2012-12/26/c_132065195.htm |title=Japan's Fukuoka wipes out over 4,600 poisonous red-back spiders&nbsp;<U+2014> Xinhua &#124; English.news.cn |publisher=News.xinhuanet.com |date=2012-12-26 |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> In September 2012, a woman was hospitalised after being bitten by one in the Higashi Ward of Fukuoka City.<ref name="FukuokaNow">{{cite web | publisher= Fukuoka Now magazine | title= Woman Bitten by Deadly Redback Spider | url= http://fukuoka-now.com/news/woman-bitten-by-deadly-redback-spider/ | accessdate=6 September 2012}}</ref> Warning signs about redback spiders have been posted in parks around the city, as Japan has had no dangerous venomous spiders before now. This has led to confusion in Japan, since the native spider ''[[Latrodectus elegans]]'' is also commonly known as the redback spider.<ref name="xinhuanet1"/>

Redback spiders are also found in small colonies in areas of New Zealand. They are frequently intercepted by quarantine authorities, often among steel or car shipments.<ref name="distributions paper">{{cite doi|10.1007/s10530-010-9885-6}}</ref> They were introduced into New Zealand in the early 1980s and now are found around Central [[Otago]] (including [[Alexandra, New Zealand|Alexandra]], [[Bannockburn, New Zealand|Bannockburn]] and near [[Wanaka]]) in the South Island<ref name="distributions paper"/><ref name="Slaughter"/> and [[New Plymouth]] in the North Island.<ref name="MAF">{{cite journal | author = Reed, C.; Newland, S.; Downs, J.; Forbes, V.; Gilbert, S. | title = MAF Biosecurity Pest Risk Assessment: Spiders Associated With Table Grapes From United States of America (State of California), Australia, Mexico and Chile | version = | publisher = MAF Biosecurity | date = September 2002 | url = http://www.biosecurity.govt.nz/files/regs/imports/risk/spiders-grapes-ra.pdf | accessdate =  18 February 2007}}</ref> Colonies have also been established in greenhouses in [[Belgium]], and isolated observations indicate a possible presence in [[New Guinea]], the [[Philippines]], and [[India]].<ref name="distributions paper"/> Some redbacks were found in Preston, [[Lancashire]], England after a container of parts arrived from Australia; some may have escaped into the countryside before pest controllers could destroy them.<ref name="Metro">{{cite web | publisher= Metro | title= Deadly Australian spiders 'invading' the UK, one field at a time  | url= http://www.metro.co.uk/weird/832600-deadly-australian-spiders-invading-the-uk-one-step-at-a-time | date = 24 June 2010| accessdate=24 June 2010}}</ref> Authorities in the [[United Arab Emirates]] warn residents and visitors of redback spiders, which have been present since 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/environment/redback-spiders-are-back-don-t-panic-urges-dubai-municipality-1.1155440|title=Redback spiders are back: don't panic, urges Dubai Municipality|first=Mariam M.|last=Al Serkal|date=7 March 2013|accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref>

==Bites==
===Prevalence===
The redback and its kin in the genus ''Lactrodectus'' are among the most dangerous spider genera, alongside funnel-web spiders (''[[Atrax]]'' and ''[[Hadronyche]]''), banana spiders (''[[Phoneutria]]'') and recluse spiders (''[[Loxosceles]]'').<ref name="Amo-Redback">{{cite web | author=Australian Museum | title=Spider Facts | url=http://australianmuseum.net.au/Spider-facts | accessdate=20 September 2013|date=6 May 2013}}</ref> Hundreds<ref name="distributions paper"/> or thousands of people are thought to be bitten by redback spiders each year across Australia.<ref name=White1998/> Of all Australian spider bites with significant medical effects, redbacks are responsible for a large majority.<ref name="bite study"/> The larger female spider is responsible for almost all cases of redback spider bites in humans.<ref name="isbister"/> The bite of a juvenile female appears to have similar potency to that of a mature female.<ref name="isbister"/> The smaller male spider was thought to be unable to envenomate a human, although male bites have been reported. The rarity of male bite reports is probably due to the male's smaller size and proportionally smaller fangs, rather than the male being incapable of biting or lacking venom of potency similar to the female's. Cases have shown the male bite usually only produces short-lived, mild pain.<ref name="isbister"/> Most bites occur in the warmer months between December and April, in the afternoon or evening.<ref name="isbister"/><ref name="sutherland">{{cite journal |author=Sutherland, S.; Trinca, J. |title=Survey of 2144 cases of Redback spider bites: Australia and New Zealand, 1963<U+2014>1976 |journal=Medical Journal of Australia |volume=2 |issue=14 |pages=620<U+2013>623 |year=1978 |pmid=732670}}</ref> As the female redback is slow-moving, and rarely leaves its web, bites generally occur as a result of a person placing a hand or other body part too close to the web, such as when reaching into dark holes or wall cavities. Bites often also occur due to a spider hidden in clothes or shoes.<ref name="White"/><ref name=Ibister2004/> One study reported 46% of bites occurring on distal extremities, 25% on proximal limbs, 21% on the trunk, and 7% on the head or neck.<ref name=Ibister2004/> In some cases the same spider bites a victim multiple times.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article122074552 |title=Spider Bite Proves Fatal. |newspaper=[[Queensland Times|Queensland Times (Ipswich) (Qld. : 1909 <U+2013> 1954)]] |location=Ipswich) (Qld.) |date=26 February 1940 |page=6 Edition: DAILY. |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article98108718 |title=General News. Bitten by Redback Spider |newspaper=[[Western Star and Roma Advertiser|Western Star and Roma Advertiser (Toowoomba, Qld. : 1875 <U+2013> 1948)]] |location=Toowoomba, Qld. |date=25 March 1936  |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

===Toxicology===
Venom is produced by glands in the cephalothorax, and expelled venom travels through paired ducts from the cephalothorax, exiting through the tip of the spider's hollow fangs. The venom of the redback spider is thought to be similar to other ''Latrodectus'' spiders, and contains a number of high-molecular-weight proteins, one of which, [[alpha-latrotoxin]] (a [[neurotoxin]]), is active in humans.<ref name="NicholsonGraudins">{{cite journal|last1=Nicholson|first1=Graham M.|last2=Graudins|first2=Andis|title=Spiders of medical importance in the Asia-Pacific: Atracotoxin, latrotoxin and related spider neurotoxins|journal=Clinical and Experimental Pharmacology and Physiology|volume=29|issue=9|year=2002|pages=785<U+2013>794|issn=0305-1870|pmid= 12165044| doi=10.1046/j.1440-1681.2002.03741.x}}</ref> In [[vertebrates]], alpha-latrotoxin produces its effect through destabilization of cell membranes and degranulation of nerve terminals, resulting in the release of neurotransmitters; it causes uncontrolled release of [[acetylcholine]], [[norepinephrine]], and [[Gamma-aminobutyric acid|GABA]]. The release of these neurotransmitters leads to the clinical manifestations of envenomation.<ref name="White">{{cite book | editor = Meier, J.; White, J. | title = Handbook of clinical toxicology of animal venoms and poisons | year = 1995 | publisher = CRC Press | isbn = 0-8493-4489-1}}</ref> At concentrations of 200&nbsp;ng/ml, the venom also deforms human red blood cells, an effect common to the venom of [[Apis mellifera|bees]], the [[Hapalochlaena maculosa|blue-ringed octopus]], and a range of snakes.<ref>{{cite doi|10.1016/0041-0101(95)00014-D}}</ref> Redback venom is considered the deadliest venom (for equal quantities) of any Australian spider.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article106949922 |title=Australia's deadliest spider. |newspaper=[[Canberra Times|The Canberra Times (ACT : 1926 - 1995)]] |location=ACT |date=2 December 1966 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

===Symptoms===
Bites from redback spiders produce a syndrome known as [[latrodectism]], with symptoms similar to bites from other ''Latrodectus'' spiders. The syndrome is generally characterised by extreme pain.<ref name="Slaughter">{{cite journal |author=Slaughter, R. J.; Beasley, D. M.; Lambie, B. S.; Schep, L. J. |title=New Zealand's venomous creatures |journal=[[The New Zealand Medical Journal]] |volume=122 |issue=1290 |pages=83<U+2013>97 |year=2009 |pmid=19319171 |url=http://www.nzma.org.nz/journal/122-1290/3494/}}</ref><ref name=Ibister2004>{{cite journal|last=Isbister|first=Geoffrey K.|coauthors=White, Julian|title=Clinical consequences of spider bites: recent advances in our understanding|journal=Toxicon|month=April|year=2004|volume=43|issue=5|pages=477<U+2013>492|doi=10.1016/j.toxicon.2004.02.002}}</ref>  A red spot is usually visible at the puncture site.<ref name=MorningBulletin1954/> The bite may be painful from the start, but sometimes only feels like a pinprick or mild burning sensation. Within an hour, victims generally develop more severe local pain with local swelling and sometimes [[piloerection]] (goosebumps). Pain, swelling and redness can spread proximally from the site.<ref name=Ibister2004/> Systemic envenoming is heralded by swollen or tender regional [[lymph nodes]]; associated features include [[malaise]], nausea, vomiting, abdominal or chest pain, generalised sweating, headache, fever, [[hypertension]] and [[tremor]].<ref name="Slaughter"/><ref name="isbister"/><ref name="White"/><ref name="Vetter">{{cite journal |author=Vetter, R. S.; Isbister, G. K. |title=Medical aspects of spider bites |journal=[[Annual Review of Entomology]] |volume=53 |issue= |pages=409<U+2013>429 |year=2008 |month= |pmid=17877450 |doi= 10.1146/annurev.ento.53.103106.093503|url=}}</ref> Rare complications include seizure, coma, pulmonary edema, respiratory failure or localised skin infection.<ref name="sutherland"/> Localised sweating and stiffness may occur at the bite site, and lymphatic involvement may result in lower limb pain.{{sfn|Brunet|1997|p=26}} Local symptoms typically develop within an hour while systemic effects may occur after a number of hours, or rarely, they may be delayed for more than 24 hours.<ref name="sutherland"/><ref name="Jelinek1989">{{cite journal |author=Jelinek, G. A.; Banham, N. D.; Dunjey, S. J. |title=Red-back spider-bites at Fremantle Hospital, 1982-1987|journal=Medical journal of Australia |volume=150 |issue=12 |pages=693<U+2013>695 |year=1989 |pmid= 2733615}}</ref> Severe pain often persists for over 24<U+2013>36 hours after being bitten.<ref name="bite study"/><ref name=Ibister2004/> Historical sources show that when left untreated, the bite can cause "great suffering" for some weeks,<ref name=Queenslander1923>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article22646978 |title=Poisonous Spider Bites |newspaper=[[The Queenslander|The Queenslander (Brisbane, Qld. : 1866 <U+2013> 1939)]] |location=Brisbane, Qld. |date=8 September 1923  |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and occasional fatalities.<ref name=avru/> Unlike some other Australian spiders, redback wounds do not [[necrosis|necrose]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Young|first=Anna R.|coauthors=Pincus, Steven J.|title=Comparison of enzymatic activity from three species of necrotising arachnids in Australia: Loxosceles rufescens, Badumna insignis and Lampona cylindrata|journal=Toxicon|year=2001|month=February<U+2013>March|volume=39|issue=2-3|pages=391<U+2013>400|doi=10.1016/S0041-0101(00)00145-8}}</ref>

===Treatment===
Treatment is based on the severity of the bite; the majority of cases do not require medical care and patients with localised pain, swelling and redness usually only require local application of ice and routine [[analgesic]]s. Hospital assessment is recommended if simple analgesia does not resolve local pain or clinical features of systemic envenoming occur.<ref name="WhiteCSL">{{cite book | last = White | first = Julian | title = A clinician's guide to Australian venomous bites and stings| publisher = CSL Ltd| location = Melbourne | year = 2013 | pages = 303<U+2013>315| doi = | isbn = 9780646579986}}</ref><ref name="Murray">{{cite book | last = Murray | first = L. | coauthors = Daly, F.; Little, M.; Cadogan, M.| title = Toxicology handbook| publisher = Churchill Livingstone| location = Sydney | year = 2011 | pages = 470<U+2013>479| doi = | isbn = 978-0729539395}}</ref> In more severe bites (2<U+2013>4% of cases),<ref name=Booth2008/> the definitive treatment consists of administering redback [[antivenom]], which will usually relieve symptoms of systemic envenoming.<ref name="nationalgeo">{{cite web|author=USA |url=http://video.nationalgeographic.com.au/video/animals/bugs-animals/spiders-and-scorpions/redback-spider-predation/ |title=Video&nbsp;<U+2014> Deadly Cousin: The Redback Spider&nbsp;<U+2014> National Geographic |publisher=Video.nationalgeographic.com.au |date= |accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref> Antivenom is indicated in anyone suffering symptoms consistent with ''Latrodectus'' envenoming. Particular indications for using antivenom are pain and swelling spreading proximally from site, distressing local or systemic pain refractory to simple analgesia, chest pain, abdominal pain, or excessive sweating.<ref name="White"/><ref name="nationalgeo" />

Currently, this antivenom is recommended by the manufacturer to be given [[intramuscularly]] (IM) rather than [[intravenously]] (IV),<ref name="proinfo">{{cite web|url=http://www.csl.com.au/s1/cs/auhq/1196562765747/Web_Product_C/1196562644318/ProductDetail.htm|title=Redback Antivenom Product Information|year=2009|work=|publisher=CSL Ltd|location=Melbourne, Australia|doi=|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> although some have suggested IM antivenom is not as effective as IV antivenom,<ref name="isbister"/><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1046/j.1442-2026.2002.00356.x |author=Isbister, Geoff |title=Failure of intramuscular antivenom in Redback spider envenoming |journal=Emergency Medicine Australasia |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=436<U+2013>439 |year=2002 |pmid=12534488}}</ref> because IM antivenom takes longer to reach the blood serum.<ref name="serum study">{{cite doi|10.1111/j.1365-2125.2007.03004.x}}</ref> Due to these concerns IV is now the recommended route of administration in Australian practice.<ref name="WhiteCSL"/><ref name="Murray"/> Adverse reactions to redback antivenom including [[anaphylaxis]] and [[serum sickness]] are rare,<ref name="CSL">{{cite web | author= White, J. | title= CSL antivenom handbook | url= http://www.toxinology.com/generic_static_files/cslb_index.html | accessdate=18 February 2007}}</ref> only occurring in 0.54 and 1.7% of cases respectively.<ref name="sutherland"/> While it is rare that patients report symptoms lasting weeks or month following a bite,<ref name="isbister"/> this antivenom has been reported as effective in the relief of chronic symptoms when administered weeks or months after a bite,<ref>{{cite journal |author=Banham, N.; Jelinek, G.; Finch, P. |title=Late treatment with antivenom in prolonged Redback spider envenomation |journal=Medical Journal of Australia |volume=161 |issue=6 |pages=379<U+2013>381 |year=1994 |pmid=8090117}}</ref><ref name="Wells">{{cite journal |author=Wells, C. L.; Spring, W. J. |title=Delayed but effective treatment of red-back spider envenomation|journal=Medical journal of Australia |volume=164 |issue=7 |pages=447 |year=1996 |pmid= 8609868  |url=}}</ref> however, in the vast majority of cases, it is administered within 24 hours.<ref name="sutherland"/> Doses are the same for both children and adults,<ref name="nationalgeo" /> typically a dose of 2 vials IV is administered followed by an additional 2 vials if there is no response after 2 hours.<ref name="WhiteCSL"/><ref name="Murray"/> The redback antivenom also appears beneficial in cases of latrodectism caused by ''Steatoda'' spiders,<ref>{{cite journal|last=South|first=Mike|coauthors=Wirth, Peter; Winkel, Ken D.|title=Redback Spider Antivenom used to Treat Envenomation by a Juvenile Steatoda Spider|journal=Medical Journal of Australia|year=1998|month=December|volume=169|issue=11|page=642|url=https://www.mja.com.au/journal/1998/169/11/redback-spider-antivenom-used-treat-envenomation-juvenile-steatoda-spider}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Graudins|first=Andis|coauthors=Gunja, Narendra; Broady, Kevin W.; Nicholson, Graham M.|title=Clinical and in vitro evidence for the efficacy of Australian red-back spider (Latrodectus hasselti) antivenom in the treatment of envenomation by a Cupboard spider (Steatoda grossa)|journal=Toxicon|month=June|year=2002|volume=40|issue=6|pages=767<U+2013>775|doi=10.1016/S0041-0101(01)00280-X}}</ref> and animal studies are positive for its use against envenomation from other widow spiders.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Graudins|first=Andis|coauthors=Padula, Matthew; Broady, Kevin; Nicholson, Graham M.|title=Red-back spider (latrodectus hasselti) antivenom prevents the toxicity of widow spider venoms|journal=Annals of Emergency Medicine|year=2001|month=February|volume=37|issue=2|pages=154<U+2013>160|doi=10.1067/mem.2001.113033}}</ref>

Historical first aid included the application of [[ligature (medicine)|ligatures]] and [[alkaline]] solutions,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23033857 |title=Don't Panic, But Treat Red-back Spider with Caution, Say Venom Experts |newspaper=[[The Argus (Australia)|The Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 <U+2013> 1957)]] |location=Melbourne, Victoria |date=6 January 1951  |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> or the provision of warmth and black coffee.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article67674357 |title=RED-BACK SPIDER. |newspaper=[[Advocate|Advocate (Burnie, Tas. : 1890 <U+2013> 1954)]] |location=Burnie, Tasmania |date=7 September 1929 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At times it was recommended to make incisions around the bite and suck the venom out, while promoting bleeding,<ref name="autogenerated3"/> and then applying tobacco juice.<ref>{{cite wikisource | class=book| first= Wilhelmina |last=Rawson | chapter = | wslink = Australian enquiry book of household and general information | title = Australian Enquiry Book of Household and General Information | year = 1894 | page =165 <!-- | wspage = 169 not working yet-->  | publisher = Pater & Knapton, Printers & Publishers | issn = | scan = Page:Australian enquiry book of household and general information.djvu/169}}</ref> Historical hospital treatments for redback bites include injections of [[strychnine]] and [[cocaine]].<ref name=Camperdown1893/>

===Prognosis===
Redback spider bites rarely cause significant [[morbidity]], and deaths are even more rare.<ref name="isbister">{{cite journal |last=Isbister|first=Geoffrey K.|coauthor=Gray, Michael R.|title=Latrodectism: a prospective cohort study of bites by formally identified Redback spiders |journal=Medical Journal of Australia |volume=179 |issue=2 |pages=88<U+2013>91 |year=2003 |pmid=12864719|url=https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2003/179/2/latrodectism-prospective-cohort-study-bites-formally-identified-redback-spiders}}</ref> Throughout Australian history, at least 14 deaths from redbacks have been recorded.<ref name=avru>{{cite web|url=http://www.avru.org/compendium/biogs/A000006b.htm |work=The Australian Venom Compendium |author=Alafaci, Annette |title=Redback Spiders |publisher=Australian Venom Research Unit |date= 25 August 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=Booth2008>{{cite journal |author=Booth, Carol |title=Along Came A Spider |journal=Australian Geographic  |year=2008|month=July<U+2013>September|url=http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/along-came-a-spider.htm}}</ref> A significant proportion of bites will not result in envenomation or any symptoms developing, only about 20% of bite victims require treatment with the antivenom.<ref name=White1998>{{cite journal |author=White, J. |title=Envenoming and antivenom use in Australia |journal=Toxicon |volume=36 |issue=11 |pages=1483<U+2013>1492 |year=1998 |pmid=9792162 |doi=10.1016/S0041-0101(98)00138-X}}</ref> Children, the elderly, or those with serious medical conditions are at much higher risk of severe effects and death resulting from a bite.<ref name="White"/> Infants have died within hours of a bite, but adult fatalities have taken up to 30 days.<ref name=MorningBulletin1954>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57311162 |title=Nature notes red-backs and black widow |newspaper=[[The Morning Bulletin|Morning Bulletin (Rockhampton, Qld. : 1878 <U+2013> 1954)]] |location=Rockhampton, Queensland |date=2 March 1954 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> No deaths (or possibly one)<ref name=Warden1989/> have been reported since the introduction of [[antivenom]] in 1956.<ref name="Wiener">{{cite journal |last=Wiener|first=Saul |title=Latrodectism: a prospective cohort study of bites by formally identified Redback spiders |journal=Medical Journal of Australia |volume=179 |issue=8 |pages=455<U+2013>456 |year=2003 |pmid=14558881|url=http://www.mja.com.au/public/issues/179_08_201003/letters201003_fm-8.html}}</ref> In an Australian study of 750 emergency hospital admissions for spider bites where the spider was definitively identified, 56 were from redbacks. Of these, 37 had significant pain lasting over 24 hours, but only six were treated with the antivenom.<ref name="bite study">{{cite doi|10.1093/qjmed/95.11.723}}</ref>

==Cultural impact==
[[File:redback back view.jpg|thumb|130px|right|The distinctive red stripe of the redback spider]]
[[Indigenous Australians]] in New South Wales mixed the venom with that of snakes and pine tree gum to form a broth used to coat spear tips.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article64034545 |title=The Aborigines of New South Wales<U+2014> their Habits, Laws, and Customs. |newspaper=[[Illustrated Sydney News|Illustrated Sydney News (NSW : 1853 <U+2013> 1872)]] |location=NSW |date=14 April 1883  |page=14 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> [[Slim Newton]] popularised redbacks in his song "Redback on the Toilet Seat", which won the [[Golden Guitar]] at the first [[Country Music Awards of Australia]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|title=Slim Newton|publisher=countrymusic.com.au|year=1998|url=http://www.countrymusic.com.au/bellbird/Biographies/Slim%20Newton.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bellbird Music|publisher=countrymusic.com.au|year=2009|url=http://www.countrymusic.com.au/bellbird/}}</ref>  <!--The song is often erroneously ascribed to [[Slim Dusty]].[http://www.onlysydney.com.au/slim-newton-redback-on-the-toilet-seat]-->[[The Angels (Australian band)|The Angels]]' 1992 album ''[[Red Back Fever]]''<ref>{{cite book|title=The Dictionary of Performing Arts in Australia: Opera, Music, Dance|year=1996|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=9781863738989|url=http://books.google.com.au/books?id=ELACebeQEgcC&lpg=PA9&dq=red%20back%20fever%20angels&pg=PA9#v=onepage&q=red%20back%20fever%20angels&f=false|author=Atkinson, Ann; Knight, Linsay; McPhee, Margaret|page=9}}</ref> described sightings of hand-sized redback spiders in outback Australia near [[Pine Gap]]. [[Matilda Bay Brewing Company]] produces a wheat beer called Redback,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EX5VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_ZYDAAAAIBAJ&dq=matilda-bay-brewing&pg=3117%2C632338|title=Hoppy flavors fit company for food|newspaper=The Age|date=23 August 1988|page=31}}</ref> with the distinctive red stripe as the logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brewsnews.com.au/2012/10/would-the-real-first-matilda-bay-beer-please-stand-up/ |title=Would the real first Matilda Bay beer please stand up? &#124; Australian Brews News |publisher=Brewsnews.com.au |date=2 October 2012 |accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> The [[South Australian Cricket Association]] has registered the name [[Southern Redbacks]] for their team,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/saca-goes-in-to-bat-on-logo/story-e6frea83-1111116848650 |title=SACA goes in to bat on logo |publisher=The Advertiser |date=6 July 2008 |last=Lower|first=Gavin |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> which is also known as the West End Redbacks due to its sponsorship agreement with South Australian brewer, [[West End Draught|West End]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redbacks.com.au/ |title= Home |work=West End Redbacks |publisher=self |date=29 August 2013 |accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref>

